The article discusses a soon-to-be released National Action Plan to Combat Human Trafficking. The plan focuses on four pillars: prevention, protection, prosecution, and partnerships. It includes priority actions such as strengthening efforts to address human trafficking in global supply chains, improving support for victims, and enhancing law enforcement's ability to investigate and prosecute traffickers. The plan also emphasizes the importance of partnerships with various stakeholders, including faith-based groups, to combat human trafficking. The Department of State, Department of Justice, and Department of Homeland Security are highlighted as key agencies involved in implementing the plan. The article also addresses questions about the politicization of human trafficking and the administration's efforts to address the issue at the southern border.